<p>Fig. <a href="#fig:vadd-graph-parallelogram-4v">3</a> shows the results of $\vec{r} _{1+2} = \vec{r}_1 + \vec{r}_2$ (left), $\vec{r} _{1+2+3} = \vec{r}_3 + \vec{r} _{1+2}$ (center), and $\vec{r} _{1+2+3+4} = \vec{r}_4 + \vec{r} _{1+2+3}$ (right), where in each step only one vector is added to the other. Actually, we can also do in another way, e.g. $(\vec{r}_1 + \vec{r}_2) + (\vec{r}_3 + \vec{r}_4) = \vec{r} _{1+2} + \vec{r} _{3+4} = \vec{r} _{1+2+3+4}$.</p>

